<subSubSection id="B4D765071F75FFF5FF48FD0E3F22D8A4" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="FC72368C1F75FFF5FF48FD0E3F22D8A4" blockId="25.[151,1437,701,1367]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
DIAGNOSIS. This species is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="3BCD4D0F1F75FFF5FCD7FD0E3FDAD88D" authorityName="Phillips &amp; Powell" authorityYear="2007" box="[776,900,701,726]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Amorbia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiapas">
<emphasis id="CEB9EA9E1F75FFF5FCD7FD0E3FDAD88D" box="[776,900,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">A. chiapas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="3BCD4D0F1F75FFF5FC1FFD0E380AD88D" authorityName="Phillips &amp; Powell" authorityYear="2007" box="[960,1108,701,726]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Amorbia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="potosiana">
<emphasis id="CEB9EA9E1F75FFF5FC1FFD0E380AD88D" box="[960,1108,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">A. potosiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the light scaling on the frons and the presence of struts of the socii.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B4D765071F75FFF5FF19FCBE3D98DED4" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph id="FC72368C1F75FFF5FF19FCBE3FE5DE3C" blockId="25.[151,1437,701,1367]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
DESCRIPTION. MALE. FW length 12.4 mm (n = 1). HEAD: Frons convex, white scaled, vertex smooth, straw yellow. Antenna with pale brown scaling. Labial palpus 2.0X length of antennal space, junction of segment II and III an oblique angle, dark golden honey-colored laterally, paler on inner surface. THORAX: Dorsum smooth scaled, brown, tegula lighter. FW ground color light brown, subbasal, median, and subterminal fasciae dark brown, well defined. Costal fold absent. HW beige with apex light brown. ABDOMEN: Pale brown. Genitalia as in 
<figureCitation id="64F62A091F75FFF5FE78FC663DA5D9B4" box="[423,507,981,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 71–72" captionStartId="74.[151,269,1631,1655]" captionTargetBox="[235,1386,190,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-36@74.[158,1399,158,1607]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURES 71–72. Male genitalia of Amorbia, valvae spread, aedeagus removed. 71, A. chiapas; 72, A. potosiana." pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
(slide # EPR10, VBC, 
<collectingCountry id="84DA761C1F75FFF5FCCAFC663F2FD9B4" box="[789,881,981,1007]" name="Mexico" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion id="3E09F86E1F75FFF5FCA1FC66384BD9B4" box="[894,1045,981,1007]" country="Mexico" name="Nuevo Leon" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Nuevo León</collectingRegion>
, Potosí; n = 1). Uncus extending beyond socii. Struts of the socii present. Transtilla rectangular, spines distributed evenly. Valva subrectangular. Sacculus sclerotized, emarginate, extending beyond margin of valva as small terminal lobe. Aedeagus 0.95X length of valva, slender, mostly straight, curved in distal 0.25.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FC72368C1F75FFF5FF19FBC63D98DED4" blockId="25.[151,1437,701,1367]" box="[198,454,1141,1167]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">FEMALE. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
